post_text:
August 27, 2020

Dear Tri-County Community:

Tri-County School Corporation was notified today of a positive result for COVID-19 within the school corporation. Please be aware that due to the HIPAA Act, which protects the individual’s health information, this is all the information we can disclose.

If your child was in close contact, you received a phone call from a school nurse or school administrator. “Close contact” is defined as being within 6 feet of someone for more than 15 minutes who have tested positive.

If you have any additional questions or concerns, please reach out to your building level administrator, school nurse, or me personally at the corporation office. All contact information can be found on our website at trico.k12.in.us.

Tri-County anticipates safely reopening the schools on Monday, August 31, 2020. During the initial closure, we will not conduct remote learning or eLearning

Thank you for your continued support and cooperation as we work together through these uncharted waters.

Yours in Education

Patrick Culp, Superintendent

post_text:
Preschool and Kindergarten First Day of School

While TCP will not have a kindergarten round-up or open house event, the TCP staff understands that a child’s very first day of school is an important moment for families.
Thursday morning parents of preschool and kindergarten students can walk their child to class at 8:30am. The afternoon preschool class can be walked to the classroom at 12:15pm. We prefer that first and second grade students arrive at school at their normal time so we can limit the number of people in the hallways.
Visitors will need to wear a face covering and go through our new Raptor visitor screening system before going to the classroom. TCP staff will be ready with a warm welcome for our new students and help them transition to being at school.

post_text:
PARENTS OF INCOMING 7TH GRADE STUDENTS

Camp Cavalier is tomorrow from 10:00 to 3:00. Buses will pick up at TCP at 9:30 and TCI at 9:45 for any 7th grade student needing a ride to the high school. At the end of Camp Cavalier, buses will transport students back to TCP and TCI by approximately 3:15.

Parents can drop off/pick up at the high school as well. Lunch is Subway (ham or turkey). Disposable masks will be available for any student needing one. Come join us for a fun day!

Water fountains are shut off, but students can bring a water bottle and there will be bottled water available.

Students do not need to bring any books or supplies with them.

This is Devin, one of our amazing seniors! Seniors who want to participate and have not yet filled out the form, please go to: https://bit.ly/2VIWRJ3

Devin's quiet demeanor and infectious smile have brightened the hallways of Tri-County. He is willing to work hard and is respectful. During his high school years, he ran Cross Country and Track. Devin also participated in 4-H and FFA. His plans for next fall are to attend Purdue for Pre-Medicine while taking classes to become a CNA to start his career. When Devin grows up, he plans on being a physician that concentrates in cardiology. Congratulations Devin!

post_text:
This is it TC! Our last daily story is "Dex: The Heart of a Hero". We know the past couple of months have been different, and at times difficult. We want to thank you for joining us and hope we brought a little bit of joy to your day. We want you to know that you are ALL heroes to us. Students and families have been amazing during these changes and times of remote learning. We want to thank each and every one of you and we can't wait to see you all!

Enjoy your summer!

This is Sarah, one of our amazing seniors! Seniors who want to participate and have not yet filled out the form, please go to: https://bit.ly/2VIWRJ3 Remember, you must be logged into your school email account in order to open this.

Sarah is a dedicated young lady who is willing to work hard and ask questions. Her beautiful smile is contagious. While attending Tri-County Sarah participated in Volleyball, Track and Field, and was the Girl’s Basketball Manager. She was also a member of NHS, SADD, Student Council, Cavalier Couriers, FFA, BPA, and participated in Every 15 Minutes. She plans to attend Ivy Tech in the fall and when she grows up she wants to be happy. Congratulations Sarah!

This is Keahi, one of our amazing seniors! Seniors who want to participate and have not yet filled out the form, please go to: https://bit.ly/2VIWRJ3 Remember, you must be logged into your school email account in order to open this.

Keahi is Valedictorian of the Class of 2020. He is very bright and driven. He knows exactly what he wants in life, and has the drive to get it done. Keahi is a polite young man and a deep thinker. Keahi participated in Football, Track & Field, Wrestling, Baseball and Marching Band while in high school. He was also a member of the R.I.P. Squad, National Honor Society, and the Student Leader Board. Keahi plans on attending Indiana University in the fall to study Law and Public Policy. When he grows up, he plans on becoming a lawyer. “But of course, that’s always subject to change so check back with me in 15-20 years, and I’ll be able to tell you then.” Congratulations Keahi!

Attention Tri-County Community Members:

On Sunday, 5/31, there will be a parade honoring our graduates of the Class of 2020. The seniors will be traveling through Wolcott first, then making their way to Remington. Parade will start at approximately 5pm through Wolcott. Please come outside and line the route in both towns to honor our seniors. Posted are the routes through both towns and the plans to take Division Road to avoid the truck stop area.

Congratulations to the Class of 2020!

Every year the sixth grade class attends a simulated space shuttle mission at the Challenger Learning Center of Northwest Indiana, a field trip sponsored by the Tri-County Educational Fund. Students were asked to design mission patches and each year the Challenger Center selects the top 10 patches of the year. This patch was selected as a top 10 design this year!

Congratulations, Alivia, on your winning design! And thanks TCEF!

This is Blayne, one of our amazing seniors! Seniors who want to participate and have not yet filled out the form, please go to: https://bit.ly/2VIWRJ3 Remember, you must be logged into your school email account in order to open this.

Blayne is a dedicated young man who is quick to smile and share a joke with all. While in high school, Blayne was active in FFA, Business Professionals of America, and National Honor Society. Blayne is the Salutatorian of the Class of 2020. He played Varsity Baseball, was active in 4-H, and was the Junior Class Vice President. Blayne’s plans for next year are to attend Purdue University, majoring in Agricultural Economics with a minor in Political Science. When he grows up he wants to be a lobbyist for an agricultural advocacy agency. He wants to be able to influence legislative changes that can lower the amount of nationwide food wastage in order to help feed people who may be living in food deserts, are unable to afford food regularly, or who may be homeless. Congratulations Blayne!

Information on picking up student belongings and returning school devices and library books:

All student supplies and belongings are bagged, labeled, and prepared for pick-up. Please go to your child's building to pick up their belongings. Students should also return any library books, textbooks, or school-issued supplies to their respective buildings.

All student devices (grades 3rd-12th) will be dropped off at the main entrance of the high school.

At all three buildings we are requesting drivers to not leave their vehicles. A staff member will come out to assist you. If possible, please place in a bag all the items you are returning.

The following dates and times are when all three schools will be open for students and families to drop-off and pick-up items (as listed above):
Tuesday, May 26th- 12:30-5:00pm
Wednesday, May 27th- 8:30am-12:30pm
Thursday, May 28th, 12:30-5:00pm
Friday, May 29th, 8:30am-12:30pm

post_text: Attention Junior High/High School Students: On the last day of school, which is on Wednesday, 5/20, come out to the high school at 3:10pm for a drive-by with staff members. Staff will be lined up on the sidewalk, six feet apart, to greet students and send everyone off for the summer. Please use the middle parking lot entrance, since teachers will be lined up where buses normally park. Come out and celebrate the end of the school year…..everyone deserves it! Again, thank you from our staff for your hard work and diligence in completing the year. You are all heroes to us! Looking forward to seeing everyone in the fall!

post_text:
SENIOR YARD SIGN ORDERS

Anyone wanting to order a senior yard sign can contact J.R. Haskins (haskinsj@trico.k12.in.us) or Mrs. Redstone (redstoneb@trico.k12.in.us) at the high school. Each yard sign will have your selected senior’s picture on one side and the class picture on the other side. We are offering the following packages to anyone that is interested:

Package #1:
18” x 24” Senior Yard Sign
Price: $16

Package #2:
18” x 24” Senior Yard Sign
Printed Mug (11 oz.)
Price: $30

Package #3:
18” x 24” Senior Yard Sign
Printed Mug
2' x 3' Class Picture Vinyl Banner (one-sided)
Price: $50

Package #4:
5' x 3' Class Picture Vinyl Banner (one-sided)
Price: $60

When ordering, please include the student’s name that you want on your sign. Don’t hesitate to contact either one of us with questions. Orders can be placed through either of our school email addresses. Deadline to place an order will be on Friday, 5/8/2020 at 4pm. Orders will be available for pick up at the high school by Friday, 5/15/2020.

What a great way to show your support for the 2020 senior class!

Looking for something new and FREE to do during your extra time at home? Do you like Breakout boxes or rooms?

Breakout EDU Live is free for anyone to tune in and play.
To play, go to breakoutEDU.com/live at 2PM ET. No login is required.

If a student wins the game, they'll be prompted to complete a form so prizes can be sent to their parents and teacher.

Parents are encouraged to play along as well. Anyone in the world. can play, but you must live in the United States to win prizes.

post_text:
Greetings TC!

We have a handful of teachers doing some fun read alouds for their classes during our remote learning and we decided we'd like to share these with all students. Hopefully we will be sharing a story every day for your students to listen to!

Second graders are listening to How To Trap A Leprechaun today, read by Mrs. Hensler, and then are designing their own leprechaun traps. We'd love to see those second grade projects here! If anyone else wants to join in on this fun STEM project, show us what you've got!

Tri-County is providing free sack lunches to our students while the school is closed. Lunches will be available during the week of March 17th-20th at TCP and TCI. Pickup times are from 11:00am-1:00pm each day. Students can receive meals through a drive-through pick-up service in the back parking lot of both schools (walk-ups and bicycles are welcome too).

All orders for the week need to be submitted by Monday, March 16th at 10:00am. Click on the link below and complete the form if you would like to pick up a free sack lunch.

https://forms.gle/EkaaQGaHe9xPtbgc7

Please share this and help us spread the word!
